summary: was watching a stream and it just sorta reminded me of dnp for some reason. The chat asked the streamer if he was gay and he...
question: was watching a stream and it just sorta reminded me of dnp for some reason. The chat asked the streamer if he was gay and he asked if he came off as gay [as a joke], to which there was mixed responses. He said "no im not gay" and EVERYONE in the chat asked if he was bi or pan/ mentioned the fact that he stuttered. Like poor boy can't live his life and I completely understand why dnp don't answer that question
answer:
The thing is, I wouldn’t even mind the question if the answer was ever good enough for people.

Like, can you imagine if all those times Dan said “no I’m not gay, I still like girls” people went “oh okay gotcha” and that was the end of it? We’d have so many fewer problems. But that answer wasn’t good enough, and so people just keep asking, as if pestering a man for years may get them a different answer.

summary: what do you think dan and phil could do to remain relevant? because now i just think they rely on their hardcore fans and don’t...
question: what do you think dan and phil could do to remain relevant? because now i just think they rely on their hardcore fans and don’t really care about dragging in new ones. which is fine but what happens when the hardcore fans move on or get bored etc
answer:
To be real with you, I don’t think that staying relevant is something either of them care about. But if it was, if they really did want to turn their shit around, they’d need to overhaul their content a little bit. I like to use Shane and Jenna as two examples of different ways that YouTubers can be highly successful.

Jenna goes with the “one video a week” method, frequent uploading, and that’s something people like. It keeps people interested. The videos she makes might sometimes be easy and low-effort, like dying her hair or taking her dogs to the pet store, but she makes those videos hilarious.

Shane on the other hand, uploads very infrequently, but the videos he does make are movie-length and extremely high quality and very unique. So if he’s gone for three months between uploads, it’s because that video took him three months to create. The product is worth the wait.

Obviously Dan and Phil can’t just become British knockoffs of Shane and Jenna, but they could follow the same sort of model. Frequent, lower-quality, funny and lighthearted videos that keep people interested or entertained, or, infrequent but high-quality videos that people are actually willing to wait a while for.
